## 7. STOP Conditions

STOP if:

- requirement unclear
- insufficient context
- path conflict
- forbidden path required
- business rule unclear
- secret / `.env` / production config required
- Chinese encoding risk
- task has multiple high-risk intents
- implementation would create spaghetti code

## 8. UTF-8 Rules

- All text files use UTF-8.
- Python: `encoding="utf-8"`
- Node: `"utf8"`
- PowerShell: PowerShell 7 + `-Encoding utf8`
- Stop immediately if mojibake or Chinese garbling appears.

## 9. Controlled Opportunistic Fixes

Allowed when low-risk, same-cause, local, and verifiable.

Allowed examples:

- prerequisite fixes required for the current task;
- same-cause small fixes;
- import / type / test / documentation small fixes;
- small script fix that does not change business semantics.

Forbidden examples:

- secrets / tokens / production config;
- schema / migration / user data;
- permission / license / billing;
- dependency upgrade;
- cross-module refactor;
- forbidden paths;
- unclear business rules.

All controlled fixes must be recorded in ExecutionReport.

## 10. Documentation Writeback

After each task, check whether the change affects long-term project context.

If affected, update related project documents when allowed by the current CommandPack.

Common documentation categories:

- project overview / usage docs
- AI execution rules / repository rules
- project context / current state
- module boundary / architecture docs
- testing / build / gate docs
- roadmap / next phase docs
- PR summaries / changelog
- manifest / directory index

Project-specific documentation paths:

- project docs: {{PROJECT_DOCS}}
- rule docs: {{RULE_DOCS}}
- context docs: {{CONTEXT_DOCS}}
- boundary docs: {{BOUNDARY_DOCS}}
- testing docs: {{TESTING_DOCS}}
- planning docs: {{PLAN_DOCS}}
- changelog docs: {{CHANGELOG_DOCS}}
- manifest docs: {{MANIFEST_DOCS}}

If updates are needed but not authorized, report required documentation writeback in ExecutionReport.

